The short answer is: Yes, Ctrl-Backspace is likely triggering your "previous pane" logic because your terminal is interpreting Ctrl-Backspace as C-h.

In many terminal emulators (like Terminator, which you mentioned), Ctrl-Backspace sends the ASCII BS (Backspace) character, which is hex 0x08. In the world of key encodings, 0x08 is exactly what Ctrl-h sends.

Why it's happening
In your config, you have this specific line:

Code snippet
bind -n C-h run "(tmux display-message -p '#{pane_current_command}' | grep -iq vim && tmux send-keys C-h) || tmux select-pane -L"
The Conflict: When you hit Ctrl-Backspace, the terminal sends the signal for C-h.

The Match: Tmux sees C-h and executes your binding.

The Result: Since you aren't in Vim (or if you are, it sends C-h to Vim), Tmux runs select-pane -L, which moves focus to the pane on the left.

How to verify
You can test what your terminal is actually sending by running this command in your shell and then pressing Ctrl-Backspace:

Bash
cat -v
If it prints ^H, then your terminal is treating Ctrl-Backspace and Ctrl-h as identical.

How to fix it
You have two main paths depending on whether you actually want Ctrl-Backspace to delete words or if you just want it to stop switching panes.

Option 1: Change Terminal Settings (Recommended)
Most modern terminals allow you to rebind what keys send. You can go into your Terminator Preferences and ensure Backspace sends DEL (0x7f) and see if there is a specific setting for Ctrl. However, this can sometimes break other CLI tools.

Option 2: Use a different shortcut for Pane Switching
If you want to keep Ctrl-Backspace for word deletion (its usual behavior), you might need to change your Tmux navigation keys to something that doesn't collide with standard ASCII control codes.

Since you already have Ctrl-Alt-Arrows (e.g., C-M-Left) bound to the same functions, you could simply comment out the C-h, C-j, C-k, C-l lines if you don't use them frequently:

Code snippet
# bind -n C-h run "..."  <-- Comment this out to stop C-Backspace from switching panes
Option 3: Use an "Extended" Key Protocol
If you are using a very modern terminal (like Kitty, Alacritty, or Foot), you can enable the Kittens Keyboard Protocol, which allows Tmux to distinguish between C-h and Backspace. However, Terminator generally follows the older VTE standards where this collision is "baked in."

A quick note on your xsel bindings
I noticed you have a comment about tmux-yank not working with the mouse. Since you're using set -g mouse on, try adding this to your config to bridge the gap:

Code snippet
bind-key -T copy-mode-vi MouseDragEnd1Pane send-keys -X copy-pipe-and-cancel "xsel -i --clipboard"
