If cat -v shows a space, your terminal is likely sending a literal Space or a null character for that combination. However, the most common reason Ctrl-Backspace triggers select-pane -L is the ASCII 0x08 (Ctrl-h) collision.

The Likely Culprit
In many Linux terminal profiles, Backspace is mapped to Ctrl-h. When you hold Ctrl + Backspace, the terminal effectively sends the same signal as Ctrl-h.

Your config contains this line:
bind -n C-h run "(...) || tmux select-pane -L"

Tmux sees the signal, matches it to C-h, and moves your pane to the Left.

How to Confirm
Since cat -v isn't cooperating, try this inside Tmux:

Press Prefix (Ctrl-Space) then :.

Type list-keys -t root and press Enter.

Look for the C-h entry.

The Quick Fix
Comment out or remove the C-h binding in your .tmux.conf:

Code snippet
# bind -n C-h run "(...)" 
Since you already have C-M-Left (Ctrl-Alt-Left) bound to the same action, you can use that for navigation instead without the backspace interference.

